---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="FraiseQL vs Apollo Federation - Detailed Comparison"
  description="Compare FraiseQL (single-schema compiled) vs Apollo Federation (multi-service federated). Understand the differences."
>
  <div style="padding: 2rem; max-width: 1280px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1>FraiseQL vs Apollo Federation</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; color: #666;">
      Two fundamentally different approaches to scaling GraphQL architectures.
    </p>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>The Core Difference</h2>
      <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0;">
        <tr style="background: #f5f3ff;">
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"></th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">FraiseQL</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Apollo Federation</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Architecture</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Single compiled schema over one database</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Multiple services federated via gateway</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Service Organization</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Monolithic API service, modular database schema</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Multiple independent services, each with their subgraph</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Team Boundaries</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Single team or shared database ownership</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Multiple independent teams per service</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Query Execution</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Pre-compiled SQL for single database</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Gateway orchestrates resolver chains across services</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Complexity Control</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Compile-time – caught early</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Runtime – potential N+1 queries across service boundaries</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>When to Choose Apollo Federation</h2>
      <ul style="font-size: 1.05rem;">
        <li>
          <strong>Multiple independent teams</strong> – Teams own separate services and deploy independently
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Microservices architecture</strong> – Services need to evolve and scale independently
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Heterogeneous data sources</strong> – Each service has its own database technology
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Loose coupling</strong> – Want to minimize team dependencies and deployment coordination
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Composition at API layer</strong> – Prefer API-level federation over database-level joins
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Existing Node.js ecosystem</strong> – Teams comfortable with Apollo Server
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; padding: 1rem; background: #f0fdf4; border-left: 4px solid #059669; border-radius: 4px;">
        <strong>✅ Good Fit:</strong> Large enterprises with multiple teams, microservices architectures, organizations with strong DevOps/platform cultures, distributed systems.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>When to Choose FraiseQL</h2>
      <ul style="font-size: 1.05rem;">
        <li>
          <strong>Monolithic API</strong> – Single team or tight-knit team owning all business logic
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Strong consistency</strong> – Need ACID transactions across entire API
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Deterministic execution</strong> – Can't tolerate unpredictable cross-service latency
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Single database model</strong> – One logical database, possibly multi-region replicas
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Compliance requirements</strong> – Need 100% audit trail, field-level encryption
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Performance-critical</strong> – Every millisecond matters (HFT, real-time analytics)
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; padding: 1rem; background: #fef2f2; border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; border-radius: 4px;">
        <strong>✅ Good Fit:</strong> Startups with tight teams, compliance-heavy systems, performance-critical APIs, analytics platforms, fintech/crypto APIs.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Technical Comparison</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Query Execution Model</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> Single query executes as one pre-compiled SQL statement. No cross-service calls. Results always complete within single transaction.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">
        Example: `SELECT users.*, posts.*, comments.* FROM users JOIN posts ON ... JOIN comments ON ...`
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Apollo Federation:</strong> Gateway decomposes query into subgraph requests. May execute 5-10 service calls for one GraphQL query. Results composed at gateway.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">
        Example: Gateway calls `/users` service, then calls `/posts` service for each user, then `/comments` for each post (potential N+1).
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">N+1 Query Problem</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> Impossible. Compiler guarantees optimal joins. Can't accidentally fetch user, then N posts without join.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Apollo Federation:</strong> Possible. Developer must use entity batching and dataloader manually. Easy to accidentally trigger cascading service calls.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Latency Profile</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> Median latency 1-2ms. Deterministic – doesn't increase with schema complexity. P99 predictable.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Apollo Federation:</strong> Median latency 15-50ms. Increases linearly with number of service calls. P99 can spike when services are slow.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Consistency Model</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> Single database transaction. All-or-nothing semantics. If user update succeeds but post update fails, entire query rolls back.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Apollo Federation:</strong> Eventual consistency. Each service has its own transaction. If user service succeeds but post service fails, partial results.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Schema Evolution</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> Schema changes require recompilation and single coordinated deployment. Breaking changes caught by compiler.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Apollo Federation:</strong> Services evolve independently. Gateway handles composition. Easier independent deployments, harder to detect composition errors.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Auditability</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> 100% audit trail – every mutation is logged, signed, immutable. Single database owner logs everything.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Apollo Federation:</strong> Distributed audit trail – each service logs independently. Correlating mutations across services difficult. Compliance risk.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Real-World Scenarios</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario: 50-Person Engineering Organization</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Requirements:</strong> 8 independent teams, each owns services (Users, Posts, Comments, Payments, Analytics, etc.). Teams deploy independently.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Apollo Federation:</strong> ✅ Perfect. Each team owns subgraph, deploys independently. Gateway composes schema. Standard microservices pattern.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> ❌ Not designed for this. Requires single team or tightly coordinated schema ownership. Deployment would be a bottleneck.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario: Fintech API (100 req/sec, SLA &lt;5ms)</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Requirements:</strong> Ultra-low latency SLA, strong consistency on all transactions, audit trail required.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Apollo Federation:</strong> ❌ Risky. Multi-service latency adds up (15-50ms typical), hard to guarantee SLA &lt;5ms. Eventual consistency problematic for financial transactions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> ✅ Designed for this. 1-2ms deterministic latency, strong consistency, built-in audit trail.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario: Healthcare Platform (HIPAA)</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Requirements:</strong> Field-level encryption, 100% audit trail of PHI access, compliance attestation.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Apollo Federation:</strong> ⚠️ Possible but complex. Would need to implement encryption, audit logging in each service. Difficult to maintain consistency.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> ✅ Built-in. Single audit trail, field-level encryption, compliance-ready.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario: Startup API (5 Engineers, Single Database)</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Requirements:</strong> Fast development, small team, all data in single PostgreSQL. Deploy 2-3 times per week.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Apollo Federation:</strong> ❌ Overkill. Microservices overhead not justified for single team and database.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> ✅ Right size. Schema compilation, single service, simple deployment.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario: Real-Time Trading Dashboard (1000s concurrent users)</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Requirements:</strong> 1000 concurrent connections, live updates, guaranteed consistency of data.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Apollo Federation:</strong> ⚠️ Possible but challenging. Gateway becomes bottleneck, multi-service consistency hard to guarantee.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> ✅ Excellent. Single database as source of truth, live subscriptions via compiled schema, consistent view for all users.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Architectural Comparison</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">FraiseQL Architecture</h3>
      <pre><code>{`┌─────────────────────────────────┐
│  GraphQL Clients                 │
└──────────────┬──────────────────┘
               │
       ┌───────▼────────┐
       │ fraiseql-wire  │ (200K× memory efficient)
       │  (Transport)   │
       └───────┬────────┘
               │
    ┌──────────▼───────────┐
    │  FraiseQL Runtime    │
    │  (Compiled Queries)  │
    └──────────┬───────────┘
               │
      ┌────────▼─────────┐
      │  PostgreSQL      │
      │  (Single DB)     │
      └──────────────────┘`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Apollo Federation Architecture</h3>
      <pre><code>{`┌──────────────────────────────────┐
│   GraphQL Clients                │
└──────────────┬───────────────────┘
               │
        ┌──────▼───────┐
        │   Gateway    │
        │ (Composition) │
        └──────┬───────┘
               │
    ┌──────────┴──────────┬──────────┬──────────┐
    │                     │          │          │
┌───▼───┐  ┌───────┐  ┌───▼───┐ ┌──▼────┐ ┌───▼───┐
│Users  │  │ Posts │  │Comments│ │Payments│ │...   │
│Service│  │Service│  │Service │ │Service │ │Service│
└───────┘  └───────┘  └───────┘ └────────┘ └───────┘
   │          │         │         │         │
┌──▼──┐  ┌───▼──┐  ┌───▼──┐  ┌──▼──┐  ┌──▼──┐
│ DB1 │  │ DB2  │  │ DB3  │  │ DB4 │  │ ... │
└─────┘  └──────┘  └──────┘  └─────┘  └─────┘`}</code></pre>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        <strong>FraiseQL:</strong> Single API boundary, one database. Easier to reason about, simpler operations.
      </p>
      <p style="color: #666;">
        <strong>Apollo:</strong> Multiple service boundaries, multiple databases. More flexibility, more complexity.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Honest Tradeoffs</h2>
      <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0;">
        <tr style="background: #f5f3ff;">
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Dimension</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">FraiseQL Advantage</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Apollo Advantage</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Team Autonomy</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Coordinated deployment</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Independent teams</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Latency</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ 1-2ms deterministic</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">15-50ms variable</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Consistency</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Strong (ACID)</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Eventual consistency</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Deployment</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Coordinated</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Independent</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Audit Trail</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ 100% centralized</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Distributed, complex</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Operational Complexity</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Simple</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Complex</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Hybrid Approach</h2>
      <p>
        Consider using <strong>both</strong> patterns strategically:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Core API (FraiseQL)</strong> – Business logic, compliance, performance-critical features. Single team owns.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Edge Services (Apollo Federation)</strong> – Third-party integrations, experimental features, team-specific APIs. Independent teams own.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Federation Gateway</strong> – Composes core FraiseQL API with edge services. Apollo Gateway or custom solution.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        Example: Stripe uses this pattern – core payment API is highly optimized monolith, federated services for integrations.
      </p>
    </section>

    <p style="margin-top: 3rem;">
      <a href="/vs">← Back to Comparisons</a> | <a href="/">Home</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
